      "surjectivity, there exists `g : Hom Y X` such that `g ≫ f = id Y`. \n  Now, to check that `f ≫ g = id X`, we need to show that for any `h : Hom X Y`, `(f ≫ g) ≫ h = h`, but this is not directly helpful.\n  Alternatively, note that since `g ≫ f = id Y`, then `f` is a section of `g`, and hence `f` is an isomorphism with inverse `g`, because in a category, if `g ≫ f = id Y`, then `f` is injective and `g` is surjective (as maps in the set-theoretic sense if we choose one), but not necessarily `f ≫ g = id X`. \n  Hmm, maybe not. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the statement is missing an assumption that the category is non-empty or that `X` or `Y` is not empty? \n\nActually, perhaps the problem is that the statement is not correct as written, because there are categories where the right side is true but the left side is not. \n\nLet me try an example:\nLet `α` have two objects `X`, `Y` and the following non-identity morphisms:\n- `f : X → Y`, and no other morphisms (except identities).\n\nThen `Hom X Y = {f}`, and `Hom Y X = ∅`.\n- `split_mono f` would require that there exists `g : Y → X` such that `g ≫ f = id X`, but `Hom Y X = ∅`, so this is false. \n- Now, check `∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X ↦ g ≫ f)`:\n  - For `c = X`: `Hom X X = {id X}`, and `fun g : Hom X X ↦ g ≫ f = {id X ≫ f = f}`. The codomain is `Hom X Y = {f}`, so this is surjective.\n  - For `c = Y`: `Hom Y X = ∅`, so the function `fun g : Hom Y X ↦ g ≫ f` is the empty function, whose image is `∅`, but the codomain is `Hom Y Y = {id Y}`, so it is not surjective. \n\nWait, so in this case the right side is false (`c = Y` fails), and the left side is also false, so no problem yet.\n\nAnother example: the category with one object `X`, and two morphisms `id X` and `f : X → X` such that `f * f = id X` (like `ℤ/2ℤ`).\n- `split_mono f`: is there a `g : X → X` such that `g ≫ f = id X`? Yes: `g = f`.\n   Because `f ≫ f = id X`, so `g = f` works (but `f ≫ g = id X` also). \n- Now, `∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X ↦ g ≫ f)`:\n   Since there is only one object, `c = X`.\n   `Hom X X = {id X, f}`. The function is `g ↦ g ≫ f`, i.e. `id X ↦ f`, `f ↦ id X`. The codomain is `Hom X X`, which is `{id X, f}`, and the image is `{f, id X}`, so it is surjective. Hence both sides are true.\n\nAnother example: the category with two objects `X`, `Y`, and one non-identity morphism `f : X → Y`. \n- `split_mono f`: no, because there are no `g : Y → X`.\n- `∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X ↦ g ≫ f)`:\n  - For `c = X`: `Hom X X = {id X}`, `g = id X`, `g ≫ f = f`. The codomain is `Hom X Y = {f}`, so surjective.\n  - For `c = Y`: `Hom Y X = ∅`, codomain `Hom Y Y = {id Y}`, not surjective.\n\nHence, again, both sides are false.\n\nBut perhaps an example where the right side is true but the left side is false. \nIt seems hard to find, perhaps because the statement is correct. \n\nLet me try again to prove (←):\nAssume `∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X ↦ g ≫ f)`.\n- Take `c = Y`, `id Y : Hom Y Y`. There exists `g : Hom Y X` such that `g ≫ f = id Y`.\n  We must prove that `f ≫ g = id X`. \n  To do this, we can use that for `c = X`, `id X : Hom X X`, there exists `h : Hom X X` such that `h ≫ f = id X`. \n  But `h ≫ f : Hom X Y`, and `id X : Hom X X`, so unless `X = Y`, this is not possible. \n\nWait, no: if we take `c = X`, then `fun g : Hom X X ↦ g ≫ f : Hom X Y`, and `id X : Hom X X`. The codomain is `Hom X Y`, but unless there is a morphism from `X` to `Y` that is not `f`, we may not be able to find `h : Hom X X` such that `h ≫ f = id X`. \n\nIn particular, if `Hom X Y = {f}`, then `h ≫ f : Hom X Y` is always `f`, unless `h` is such that `h ≫ f` is not defined (but it always is), so `h ≫ f = f`. Thus, if `id X ≠ f` (as morphisms from `X` to `Y`?), we have no solution. \n\nBut in general, this approach seems not working. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the problem is that `Function.Surjective` is not the right condition. In Lean, `Function.Surjective` is about the underlying type, not the category. So perhaps it is not `Hom Y Y`, but the type `Hom Y Y` is nonempty and so on, and this is causing confusion.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the statement is not correctly translated, and it should have been about `Function.Bijective` instead of `Function.Surjective`.\n\nBut in the original problem statement (the Lean code), it is `Function.Surjective`, and in my proof attempt, (→) works, but (←) seems not. \n\nPerhaps the problem expects us to only prove (→), and leave (←) as an exercise that might not always hold. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps I'm missing something, and (←) is actually true. \n\nLet me think differently:\nWe have `g : Hom Y X` such that `g ≫ f = id Y`. \nThen, `f` is injective (monic), because if `h₁ ≫ f = h₂ ≫ f`, then `h₁ = h₁ ≫ (g ≫ f) = (h₁ ≫ g) ≫ f = (h₂ ≫ g) ≫ f = h₂ ≫ (g ≫ f) = h₂`. \nBut perhaps we also have that `g ≫ f = id Y` implies that `f` is",
      "\n  constructor\n  · intro h c\n    have h₁ : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), f ≫ g = id X := by\n      obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h\n      exact ⟨g, hg⟩\n    obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h₁\n    have h₂ : Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f) := h c\n    refine' ⟨g, _⟩\n    have h₃ : f ≫ g = id X := hg\n    have h₄ : g ≫ f = id X := by\n      have h₅ : Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom X X => g ≫ f) := h X\n      sorry\n    sorry\n  · intro h\n    sorry",
      "\n  constructor\n  · -- Prove the forward direction: split_mono f → ∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f)\n    intro h\n    rw [split_mono] at h\n    intro c\n    have h₁ : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), IsSection f g := by simpa [IsSection] using h\n    obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h₁\n    have h₂ : Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f) := by\n      intro y\n      use y ≫ g\n      rw [← hg]\n      <;> simp [comp_assoc]\n    exact h₂\n  · -- Prove the reverse direction: (∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f)) → split_mono f\n    intro h\n    have h₁ : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), IsSection f g := by\n      have h₂ : Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom Y X => g ≫ f) := by\n        apply h\n      obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h₂ (1 : Hom Y Y)\n      use g\n      <;> simp_all [IsSection, id_comp]\n      <;> aesop\n    rw [split_mono]\n    simpa [IsSection] using h₁",
      "\n  apply Iff.intro\n  · -- Prove the forward direction: if f is a split mono, then for all c, the map (g : Hom c X) ↦ g ≦ f is surjective.\n    intro h_split_mono c\n    rcases h_split_mono with ⟨g, hg⟩\n    have h_surj : Function.Surjective (fun g' : Hom c X => g' ≫ f) := by\n      intro h\n      -- Since f is a split mono, there exists a g such that g ≦ f = id X.\n      -- We can use this to construct a g' such that g' ≦ f = h.\n      use h ≫ g\n      calc\n        (h ≫ g) ≫ f = h ≫ (g ≫ f) := by rw [→ assoc]\n        _ = h ≫ id X := by\n          have h1 : g ≫ f = id X := by\n            simpa [IsSection] using hg\n          rw [h1]\n        _ = h := by simp [id_comp]\n    exact h_surj\n  · -- Prove the reverse direction: if for all c, the map (g : Hom c X) ↦ g ≦ f is surjective, then f is a split mono.\n    intro h_surj_all\n    -- We need to find a g such that g ≦ f = id X.\n    have h_c : Function.Surjective (fun g' : Hom Y X => g' ≫ f) := h_surj_all Y\n    -- Since the map is surjective for c = Y, there exists a g such that g ≦ f = id X.\n    have h_exists_g : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), g ≫ f = id X := by\n      have h_id : ∃ (g' : Hom Y X), g' ≫ f = id X := by\n        have h1 : Function.Surjective (fun g' : Hom Y X => g' ≫ f) := h_surj_all Y\n        have h2 : (id X : Hom X X) ∈ Set.range (fun g' : Hom Y X => g' ≫ f) := by\n          have h3 := h1 (id X)\n          obtain ⟨g', hg'⟩ := h3\n          exact ⟨g', by simpa using hg'⟩\n        obtain ⟨g', hg'⟩ := h2\n        exact ⟨g', by simpa using hg'⟩\n      obtain ⟨g', hg'⟩ := h_id\n      exact ⟨g', hg'⟩\n    -- Therefore, f is a split mono.\n    obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h_exists_g\n    refine' ⟨g, _⟩\n    <;> simp_all [IsSection]",
      "\n  constructor\n  · -- Prove the forward direction: if split_mono f, then ∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f)\n    intro h\n    have h₁ : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), g ≫ f = id X := by\n      obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h\n      exact ⟨g, hg⟩\n    intro c\n    -- Use the surjectivity condition to show that for any h : c → Y, there exists g : c → X such that g ≫ f = h\n    have h₂ : Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f) := by\n      intro h\n      -- Obtain the inverse g : Y → X such that g ≫ f = id X\n      obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h₁\n      -- Construct g' : c → X as g' = h ≫ g\n      have h₃ : Hom c Y := h\n      have h₄ : Hom c X := h₃ ≫ g\n      -- Show that (h₃ ≫ g) ≫ f = h₃\n      have h₅ : (h₃ ≫ g) ≫ f = h₃ := by\n        calc\n          (h₃ ≫ g) ≫ f = h₃ ≫ (g ≫ f) := by\n            simp [comp_assoc]\n          _ = h₃ ≫ (id X) := by rw [hg]\n          _ = h₃ := by simp\n      -- Conclude that h₃ is in the image of (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f)\n      refine' ⟨h₃ ≫ g, _⟩\n      <;> simp_all [comp_assoc]\n      <;> try simp_all [hg]\n      <;> try simp_all [id_comp]\n    exact h₂\n  · -- Prove the reverse direction: if ∀ c : α, Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom c X => g ≫ f), then split_mono f\n    intro h\n    have h₁ : Function.Surjective (fun g : Hom Y X => g ≫ f) := h Y\n    -- Obtain the inverse g : Y → X such that g ≫ f = id X\n    have h₂ : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), g ≫ f = id X := by\n      have h₃ : ∃ (g : Hom Y X), g ≫ f = id X := by\n        -- Use the surjectivity condition to find g\n        have h₄ : (id X : Hom X X) ∈ Set.range (fun g : Hom Y X => g ≫ f) := by\n          apply h₁\n          <;> simp\n        -- Obtain g such that g ≫ f = id X\n        obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h₄\n        exact ⟨g, by simpa using hg⟩\n      exact h₃\n    -- Conclude that f is a split mono\n    obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := h₂\n    refine' ⟨g, _⟩\n    <;> simp_all [hg]\n    <;> try simp_all [id_comp]\n    <;> try simp_all [comp_assoc]",
      "\n  sorry",
